item.title: About us
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
We engineer quantum effects in biology

QuBiT Lab is a team of scientists exploring the quantum world of biology, located in Westwood Los Angeles at UCLA.

Welcome to our website! We are a team of scientists who are passionate about exploring the fascinating intersection between quantum physics and biology.

Our team includes experts in AMO physics, chemistry, and biology, and we are dedicated to unlocking the secrets of quantum effects in biological systems. Our journey began in 2020, when we set out to investigate the potential of low magnetic fields to control spin-dependent chemical reactions in biology. Our goal is to use the subtle magnetic fields of the Earth to manipulate the behavior of biological molecules, paving the way for new breakthroughs in biotechnology and medicine. Our research is at the cutting edge of the field, and we are excited to share our latest findings with you. By delving deep into the quantum world of biological systems, we aim to uncover new ways of understanding and controlling the fundamental processes that underpin life itself.

Thank you for visiting our website, and we hope that you will join us on this exciting journey of discovery!

Inspiring creative work

We are constantly inspired by experimental and theoretical reports on the effects of low magnetic fields in biology, and we strive to build meaningful partnerships with other experts in the field. Our collective goal is to unlock the secrets of the quantum world of biology, and to use this knowledge to push the boundaries of biotechnology and medicine.

420 Westwood Plaza, Engineering IV, 58-113, Los Angeles 90095, US

Message us

For visitors attending the QuBiT lab, we recommend parking in parking structure #8 in a visitor spot on the roof top. Please note that parking structure #9 is permit-only except on weekends. Parking structure #8 is located in parking zone 2508.

PostDoc position: spin-dependent chemical reactions under weak magnetic fields

Our cutting-edge laboratory is looking for a talented and motivated postdoc to join our team and work on TIRF microscopy. As a postdoctoral researcher, you will have the opportunity to work on a range of exciting projects in our state-of-the-art laboratory, collaborating with other researchers to advance the field of TIRF microscopy.

We are seeking a highly motivated candidate with a PhD in a relevant field, and a proven track record of success in TIRF microscopy. The ideal candidate will have expertise in optical instrumentation, imaging, and data analysis, as well as excellent communication and organizational skills. As a postdoc in our lab, you will have access to the latest technologies and resources to support your research, including a range of TIRF microscopes and imaging equipment. You will also have the opportunity to collaborate with leading experts in the field, and to contribute to high-impact publications and presentations.

If you are passionate about TIRF microscopy and eager to make a meaningful contribution to the field, we encourage you to apply. We offer a competitive salary, excellent benefits, and a dynamic and supportive work environment that fosters creativity, innovation, and collaboration.

To apply, please submit your CV, a cover letter outlining your research experience and interests, and the contact information to cla@ucla.edu.

ESR-STM stands for "electron spin resonance scanning tunneling microscopy," which is a specialized microscopy technique used in materials science to investigate the electronic and magnetic properties of surfaces at the atomic scale.

CISS stands for "chemical shift imaging with stimulated echoes," which is a specialized magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) technique used to obtain spatially resolved spectroscopic information about the chemical composition of tissues and organs.

TIRF stands for "total internal reflection fluorescence" microscopy, which is a type of microscopy that is used to visualize the dynamics of molecules and structures at the interface between a glass coverslip and a solution.

LLS stands for "light-sheet fluorescence microscopy," which is a specialized imaging technique used in biological research to visualize the 3D structures and dynamics of living cells and organisms.

Quantum Biology GRC

March 19-26, 2023 in Galveston, TX

We are excited to announce that Qubit Lab will be attending the Quantum Biology Gordon Research Conference. The focus of the conference is on "Emerging Methodologies to Investigate Quantum Effects in Biology". We are looking forward to a productive and inspiring conference, and hope to see you there.

Quantum Biology Seminar

Feb 10, 2023 in qubit zoom room

The talk tomorrow will be given by Thomas Ebbesen, from the University of Strasbourg, and medaille d'or du CNRS! The title of the talk is "Manipulating matter by strong coupling to the vacuum field". The trainee host is Nathan Babcock, a postdoc at Howard University.
